    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-09-08T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-09-08T07:00:00-05:00" n="1153"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1153">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">767.68119/1044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-09-08T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >September 8, 1943—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1530. As the result of representations by the British Embassy and ourselves the
                    Turkish Government has decided to hereafter prohibit <pb facs="1099" n="1087"
                        xml:id="pg_1087"/> the transit thru the Straits of so-called barges of which
                    the Germans have thus far transited light.</p>
                <p>The representations made by the British and ourselves were based on information
                    to the effect that these so-called barges altho giving the outward appearance of
                    being commercial vessels were built solely for military purposes and that on
                    their arrival at Greek ports they discharge military supplies and the crews
                    immediately don German naval uniforms.</p>
                <p>The Turkish Government anticipates a vigorous protest from the German Embassy as
                    soon as the prohibition is made effective, particularly as a considerable number
                    of these barges have been constructed by the Germans during the past year in
                    Bulgarian and Rumanian ports.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
